user_message:
An agent A claimed that the following OS_FileOpenCheck code violates the MISRA C 2023 rule 8.13.
<misra_rule>
MISRA C 2023 Rule 8.13 is A pointer should point to a const-qualified type whenever possible.

</misra_rule>
<target_code>
Here is the original code of OS_FileOpenCheck.
```c
int32 OS_FileOpenCheck(const char *Filename)
{
    int32                        return_code;
    OS_object_iter_t             iter;
    OS_stream_internal_record_t *stream;

    /* Check parameters */
    OS_CHECK_POINTER(Filename);

    return_code = OS_ERROR;

    OS_ObjectIdIterateActive(LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE, &iter);

    while (OS_ObjectIdIteratorGetNext(&iter))
    {
        stream = OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET(OS_stream_table, iter.token);
        if (stream->socket_domain == OS_SocketDomain_INVALID && (strcmp(stream->stream_name, Filename) == 0))
        {
            return_code = OS_SUCCESS;
            break;
        }
    }

    OS_ObjectIdIteratorDestroy(&iter);

    return return_code;
}
```
</target_code>
<response format>
Provide your answer with these fields.
- explanation: your evaluation of the scenario provided by the agent A.
- is_report_correct: whether the report is correct or not (true/false). True means there is a violation.
</response format>
<scenario>
The agent A provided the following violation scenario:
The local variable 'stream' is declared as OS_stream_internal_record_t * but in this function it is only used for read-only access (strcmp on stream->stream_name and reading stream->socket_domain). According to MISRA C 2023 Rule 8.13 the pointer should be to a const-qualified type when possible. The call OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET returns a non-const pointer, but assigning that to a const OS_stream_internal_record_t * would be valid and appropriate. Example fix: declare 'stream' as 'const OS_stream_internal_record_t *stream;'.
</scenario>
<additional code>Here are the definitions of symbols that are close to the target function OS_FileOpenCheck:
typedef struct
{
    char   stream_name[OS_MAX_PATH_LEN];
    uint8  socket_domain;
    uint8  socket_type;
    uint16 stream_state;
} OS_stream_internal_record_t
...
OS_stream_internal_record_t OS_stream_table[OS_MAX_NUM_OPEN_FILES]
...
#define OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET(tbl, tok) (&tbl[OS_ObjectIndexFromToken(&(tok))])
...
typedef struct
{
    OS_common_record_t * base;
    OS_ObjectMatchFunc_t match;
    void *               arg;
    osal_index_t         limit;
    OS_object_token_t    token;
} OS_object_iter_t
...
#define OS_CHECK_POINTER(ptr) BUGCHECK((ptr)!=NULL,OS_INVALID_POINTER)
</additional code>

<instruction>
Judge whether the report is correct or not.
</instruction>

explanation:
Correct. In OS_FileOpenCheck the local variable 'stream' is only used for read-only accesses (reading stream->socket_domain and using strcmp on stream->stream_name). Per MISRA C 2023 Rule 8.13, the pointer should point to a const-qualified type when possible. Changing the declaration to
    const OS_stream_internal_record_t *stream;
is valid: assigning the address of a non-const object to a pointer-to-const is permitted, and the members will be treated as const for this function. Thus the agent A report is correct—this is a violation and the suggested fix is appropriate (unless there is a later need in this function to modify the pointed object).
